h with their exploitative employers. At the same time, BC’s anti-Asian and anti-Indigenous racism meant that their “whiteness” alone could define them as respectable, without the need for church affiliation. Consequently, although Christianity retained major social power elsewhere, many people in BC found the freedom to forgo church attendance or espouse atheist views. This nuanced study of mobility, gender, masculinity, and family in settler BC offers new insights into BC’s distinctive culture and into the beginnings of what has become an increasingly dominant secular worldview across Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIrreligionzBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 0aReligionxHistory. 0aSecularismzBritish ColumbiaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311127380808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016z978311127630408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311141795040uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483346240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774833462423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774833462/original  a978-3-11-127380-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-127630-4  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-141795-0  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles